<subSubSection id="C3036541FFEA8B335E8FFD24220BFC5E" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA636CAFFEA8B335E8FFD2422A8FD78" blockId="25.[189,457,694,720]" box="[189,457,694,720]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<heading id="D0EE81A6FFEA8B335E8FFD2422A8FD78" bold="true" box="[189,457,694,720]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335E8FFD2422A8FD78" bold="true" box="[189,457,694,720]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA636CAFFEA8B335E8FFD77220BFC5E" blockId="25.[189,1400,741,1014]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName id="4C194D49FFEA8B335E8FFD7722BAFD57" authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,475,741,767]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracicus" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335E8FFD7722BAFD57" box="[189,475,741,767]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ebenacobius thoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25E57A3FFEA8B335FD7FD7421FEFCA8" box="[485,671,742,768]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be distinguished from other species of the genus by its uniformly reddish integuments and the peculiar shape of prothorax in males, almost rectangular, with a very short apical constriction (
<figureCitation id="13222A4FFFEA8B335C77FCBE21C0FCEE" box="[581,673,812,838]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1857,1883]" captionTargetBox="[366,1236,269,1806]" captionTargetId="figure-15@14.[321,1266,265,1819]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 2. A–I. Habitus of males of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov. in dorsal view (part 1). A. E. curvisetis Haran gen. et sp. nov. B. E. rectirostris Haran gen. et sp. nov. C. E. duplicatus Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. grobbelaarae Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. costalis (Fåhraeus, 1844) gen. et comb. nov. F. E. thoracicus Haran gen. et sp. nov. G. E. xhosa Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. san Haran gen. et sp. nov. I. E. kuscheli Haran gen. et sp. nov. Scale bars = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6532971" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6532971/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
). The body penis is very short in this species, being at most 2 × longer than wide in dorsal view (
<figureCitation id="13222A4FFFEA8B335C4CFCDD21BAFCC2" box="[638,731,847,874]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="33.[189,232,1852,1878]" captionTargetBox="[351,1247,266,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-11@33.[339,1248,265,1815]" captionText="Fig. 6 (part 1). A–I. Male genitalia of Ebenacobius Haran gen. nov., penis in dorsal (left) and lateral (right) view.A. E. curvisetis Haran gen. et sp. nov.B. E. rectirostrisHaran gen. et sp. nov.C. E. duplicatus Haran gen. et sp. nov. D. E. grobbelaarae Haran gen. et sp. nov. E. E. costalis (Fåhraeus, 1844) gen. et comb. nov. F. E. thoracicus Haran gen. et sp. nov. G. E. xhosa Haran gen. et sp. nov. H. E. san Haran gen. et sp. nov. I. E. kuscheli Haran gen. et sp. nov. A–I = not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6536655" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6536655/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C194D49FFEA8B335CC0FCDD2771FCC1" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[754,1040,847,873]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracicus">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335CC0FCDD2771FCC1" box="[754,1040,847,873]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Ebenacobius thoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C194D49FFEA8B335A86FCC2267AFCC1" authority="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat, 2022" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[1204,1307,847,873]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xhosa" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335A86FCC2267AFCC1" box="[1204,1307,847,873]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. xhosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25E57A3FFEA8B335B17FCDD227AFC25" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in general appearance, but the latter species has convex eyes (flatter in 
<taxonomicName id="4C194D49FFEA8B335AA2FCE12651FC24" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[1168,1328,882,908]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracicus">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335AA2FCE12651FC24" box="[1168,1328,882,908]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. thoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, only slightly exceeding lateral curve of head in lateral view), males lack a distinct prosternal process (visible and directed forward in 
<taxonomicName id="4C194D49FFEA8B335FE8FC2B2116FC7A" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[474,631,952,978]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracicus">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335FE8FC2B2116FC7A" box="[474,631,952,978]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. thoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and show an internal angle on profemora (profemora smooth in 
<taxonomicName id="4C194D49FFEA8B335E8CFC4E2238FC5E" authorityName="Haran &amp; Benoit &amp; Procheş &amp; Kergoat" authorityYear="2022" box="[190,345,988,1014]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Ebenacobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="thoracicus">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335E8CFC4E2238FC5E" box="[190,345,988,1014]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">E. thoracicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3036541FFEA8B335E8FFB8F2226FB21" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA636CAFFEA8B335E8FFB8F2225FB9F" blockId="25.[189,324,1053,1079]" box="[189,324,1053,1079]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<heading id="D0EE81A6FFEA8B335E8FFB8F2225FB9F" bold="true" box="[189,324,1053,1079]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B96DEAD8FFEA8B335E8FFB8F2225FB9F" bold="true" box="[189,324,1053,1079]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA636CAFFEA8B335E8FFBD92226FB21" blockId="25.[189,1398,1099,1161]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">This species is named in reference to the specific shape of the prothorax in males, being almost rectangular.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
